483
00:28:06,167 --> 00:28:08,727
- I'm not retiring.
- Are you sick?

484
00:28:08,770 --> 00:28:11,238
- I've never felt more alive.
- Well, why?

485
00:28:11,272 --> 00:28:14,400
I have my reasons, Stuart. I want
everything sold within in one week.

486
00:28:14,442 --> 00:28:16,410
A week?
No, can't be done.

487
00:28:16,444 --> 00:28:19,004
You try and unload all those shares
that fast, the bottom will fall out.

488
00:28:19,047 --> 00:28:20,537
Just sell for whatever price
you can get.

489
00:28:20,582 --> 00:28:22,982
- It's all going to charities anyway.
- Charities?

490
00:28:23,017 --> 00:28:25,611
And, Stuart, not one
word to anybody.

491
00:28:25,653 --> 00:28:27,951
Those are my instructions.
Just sell everything

492
00:28:27,989 --> 00:28:31,618
and one week from today, I want to see
a cashier's check on my desk.

493
00:28:31,659 --> 00:28:35,026
- It won't be your desk anymore.
- Exactly.

494
00:28:44,205 --> 00:28:46,173
- Michael.
- Dad.

495
00:28:46,207 --> 00:28:48,539
- Yeah.
- You're up late.

496
00:28:50,478 --> 00:28:53,879
- Are you okay?
- Yeah, fine. Nice party?

497
00:28:53,915 --> 00:28:55,940
Yeah, okay.

498
00:28:55,984 --> 00:28:58,748
That's good. I was just standing
here thinking about

499
00:28:58,787 --> 00:29:01,381
your great-grandfather
Albar.

500
00:29:01,423 --> 00:29:03,391
I wish you had
known him.

501
00:29:03,425 --> 00:29:05,359
- Me too.
- Yeah.

502
00:29:05,393 --> 00:29:09,386
He was about your age
when he left his village in Turkey.

503
00:29:09,431 --> 00:29:12,059
Everybody thought
he was crazy.

504
00:29:12,100 --> 00:29:15,035
They said those rumors
of what's happening to other Armenians

505
00:29:15,069 --> 00:29:17,697
in the other villages,
that couldn't possibly be true.

506
00:29:17,739 --> 00:29:20,469
No no. Murdering
an entire people?

507
00:29:20,508 --> 00:29:23,477
Oh, that's impossible.

508
00:29:23,511 --> 00:29:27,003
That man knew that in this world
anything is possible.

509
00:29:27,048 --> 00:29:29,209
Every situation
is different.

510
00:29:29,250 --> 00:29:32,219
A man has to size up
each individual situation

511
00:29:32,253 --> 00:29:34,380
and then act
accordingly, right?

512
00:29:34,422 --> 00:29:36,720
And no matter what
anybody else thinks.

513
00:29:36,758 --> 00:29:39,852
He took his wife
and his two small children

514
00:29:39,894 --> 00:29:42,419
and he got out.

515
00:29:42,464 --> 00:29:45,262
One month later,
that village didn't even exist.

516
00:29:45,300 --> 00:29:47,359
Smart fella.

517
00:29:47,402 --> 00:29:49,199
Yeah.

518
00:29:49,237 --> 00:29:51,296
Well, he liked
to think things through.

519
00:29:51,339 --> 00:29:54,137
If he hadn't,
you and I wouldn't be here.

520
00:29:54,175 --> 00:29:58,271
A man has to think
things through for himself.

521
00:29:58,313 --> 00:29:59,803
Right.

522
00:29:59,848 --> 00:30:03,306
Well, this man is thinking
he ought to get some sleep.

523
00:30:03,351 --> 00:30:05,876
Gotta get up early.
Tennis date at 11:00.

524
00:30:05,920 --> 00:30:09,686
Oh, yeah, well,
you sleep well, my son.

525
00:30:11,159 --> 00:30:13,593
- I love you, Michael.
- I love you, Dad.

526
00:30:13,628 --> 00:30:17,496
- And they love you, too.
- And I love them. Good night.

527
00:30:23,605 --> 00:30:25,163
Oh, Albar,

528
00:30:25,206 --> 00:30:28,835
you saved this
family's life.

529
00:30:28,877 --> 00:30:30,868
I'll save its soul.

530
00:30:39,754 --> 00:30:42,382
Most of the money
I gave to various charities.

531
00:30:42,423 --> 00:30:46,917
Some I decided to dispose of in a more
personal manner.

532
00:31:08,416 --> 00:31:10,441
It's for you.

533
00:31:10,485 --> 00:31:14,512
You were that guy who came around
here giving away that money?

534
00:31:14,556 --> 00:31:17,081
- Yeah.
- I know people who got some of that.

535
00:31:17,125 --> 00:31:19,116
- That was you?
- Yeah.

536
00:31:19,160 --> 00:31:21,253
- You gave it all away?
- Yeah.

537
00:31:21,296 --> 00:31:23,821
- You asshole.
- Yeah.

538
00:31:23,865 --> 00:31:25,833
I think most people
would agree with you.

539
00:31:25,867 --> 00:31:28,859
Now I can't believe
that I did it,

540
00:31:28,903 --> 00:31:31,167
but at that time,
it certainly seemed logical.

541
00:31:32,173 --> 00:31:34,300
- Every last cent?
- Every last cent.

542
00:31:34,342 --> 00:31:37,334
Aram, that's the most
insane thing I've ever heard.

543
00:31:37,378 --> 00:31:40,279
- Just to force your kid to get a job?
- Oh yeah.

544
00:31:40,315 --> 00:31:42,510
Couldn't you just kick
him out of the house?

545
00:31:42,550 --> 00:31:44,984
No! He knows his
father would never let him starve.

546
00:31:45,019 --> 00:31:46,646
Took away
his incentive.

547
00:31:46,688 --> 00:31:48,349
I'm restoring
that incentive.

548
00:31:48,389 --> 00:31:51,358
Couldn't you have stashed your money
in a bank and not told him?

549
00:31:51,392 --> 00:31:53,792
Well, yeah, but...

550
00:31:53,828 --> 00:31:56,854
the truth is I'm not doing it
just for Michael.

551
00:31:56,898 --> 00:31:58,866
See, I've got
other reasons.

552
00:31:58,900 --> 00:32:00,765
I'm bored.

553
00:32:00,802 --> 00:32:03,362
The greatest pleasure
in life is becoming a success.

554
00:32:03,404 --> 00:32:06,532
Being a success is crap
compared to it.

555
00:32:06,574 --> 00:32:09,634
I'm giving myself a chance
to do that twice in a lifetime.

556
00:32:09,677 --> 00:32:12,168
I see, and how's Millie
supposed to react

557
00:32:12,213 --> 00:32:14,443
when you come home tonight,
you throw your arms up

558
00:32:14,482 --> 00:32:16,609
and say, "Honey, I'm home.
We're poor!"

559
00:32:16,651 --> 00:32:19,415
Don't you think you maybe
should have consulted her?

560
00:32:19,454 --> 00:32:21,945
Yeah, but I couldn't,
you see?

561
00:32:21,990 --> 00:32:24,481
I want Michael to think
that I've lost all my money.

562
00:32:24,525 --> 00:32:26,493
If I tell that to Millie,
she's gonna give it away

563
00:32:26,527 --> 00:32:28,051
because she's
a lousy liar.

564
00:32:28,096 --> 00:32:31,361
- Oh, then it serves her right.
- But I did it for her, too.

565
00:32:31,399 --> 00:32:35,233
- She's the third reason.
- Ah, Katourian's law.

566
00:32:35,269 --> 00:32:37,237
By making Millie
a pauper,

567
00:32:37,271 --> 00:32:39,330
you're restoring her
to a rich and full sex life.

568
00:32:39,374 --> 00:32:41,842
- Exactly.
- I hope she's properly grateful.

569
00:32:41,876 --> 00:32:44,174
It's not just the sex.

570
00:32:44,212 --> 00:32:47,511
Before we were rich,
Millie's life had purpose.

571
00:32:47,548 --> 00:32:51,575
Just as my money ruined my son,
it ruined her too.

572
00:32:51,619 --> 00:32:55,020
I'm giving Millie back a reason
for living, a sense of importance.

573
00:32:55,056 --> 00:32:57,217
By making her a pauper?

574
00:32:57,258 --> 00:32:59,226
Oh, come on.
Millie's gonna be okay.

575
00:32:59,260 --> 00:33:01,421
She won't starve
to death as long as I'm around.

576
00:33:01,462 --> 00:33:04,056
Aram, what if
you're not around?

577
00:33:04,098 --> 00:33:07,192
What if something should happen
to you while you're between fortunes?

578
00:33:07,235 --> 00:33:09,294
You think I didn't
think of that?

579
00:33:09,337 --> 00:33:11,965
I prepaid my insurance premiums
for the next 10 years.

580
00:33:12,006 --> 00:33:14,566
I think of everything.

581
00:33:17,712 --> 00:33:19,703
It's the deed
to the condo.

582
00:33:19,747 --> 00:33:22,978
Aram, you didn't
have to do this.

583
00:33:23,017 --> 00:33:26,009
Yes, I did. I won't be able to afford
the rent anymore.

584
00:33:35,463 --> 00:33:37,556
May be a while
before I can bring

585
00:33:37,598 --> 00:33:39,691
the sort of gifts
I used to.

586
00:33:41,169 --> 00:33:43,137
May I still come
and see you?

587
00:33:43,171 --> 00:33:47,403
Aram, yes, of course
you can still come see me.

588
00:33:47,442 --> 00:33:50,138
Thank you.

589
00:34:03,257 --> 00:34:05,691
- Have a good day.
- Thanks. You too.

590
00:34:23,478 --> 00:34:26,413
Michael, would you
come downstairs, please?

591
00:34:26,447 --> 00:34:28,074
- Hello, Millie.
- Hello, Aram.

592
00:34:28,116 --> 00:34:30,209
Would you sit down?
We have to talk.

593
00:34:30,251 --> 00:34:33,084
- What is it?
- Let's wait till Michael gets here.

594
00:34:33,121 --> 00:34:35,146
Hey, Dad, what's up?

595
00:34:35,189 --> 00:34:38,852
Michael, sit down.
I, uh...

596
00:34:38,893 --> 00:34:41,691
I've some bad news,
very bad news.

597
00:34:41,729 --> 00:34:43,822
- Oh my God. Somebody died.
- No.

598
00:34:43,865 --> 00:34:46,732
- You sure nobody died?
- Nobody died.

599
00:34:46,768 --> 00:34:48,565
Well, is somebody
gonna die?

600
00:34:48,603 --> 00:34:51,970
Everybody's gonna die. Please, Millie,
let me tell you what happened.

601
00:34:52,006 --> 00:34:53,564
Now...

602
00:34:59,213 --> 00:35:02,376
I made some very
bad investments lately,

603
00:35:02,416 --> 00:35:04,782
and I lost
a lot of money.

604
00:35:06,954 --> 00:35:08,979
So much money that
I've had to sell everything

605
00:35:09,023 --> 00:35:10,991
in order to cover
those losses.

606
00:35:11,025 --> 00:35:13,789
In short, this family is penniless.
We have nothing.

607
00:35:13,828 --> 00:35:15,659
- Nothing?
- Nothing.

608
00:35:15,696 --> 00:35:18,893
The entire business that took you
20 years to build, you lost it all?

609
00:35:18,933 --> 00:35:21,663
- Yeah, everything.
- God, you must feel horrible.

610
00:35:23,037 --> 00:35:25,528
All of the stores,
they're all gone?

611
00:35:25,573 --> 00:35:27,507
Yeah, all.

612
00:35:27,542 --> 00:35:29,772
- Our stocks, our government bonds?
- I had to sell 'em.

613
00:35:29,811 --> 00:35:32,712
- We still have the house?
- We never owned the house.

614
00:35:32,747 --> 00:35:35,375
The company bought the house
and leased it to us for tax purposes.

615
00:35:35,416 --> 00:35:37,407
I no longer run
the company.

616
00:35:37,451 --> 00:35:39,419
We no longer can
live in this house.

617
00:35:39,453 --> 00:35:41,353
- The cars?
- Same thing.

618
00:35:41,389 --> 00:35:42,856
The furniture?

619
00:35:42,890 --> 00:35:44,517
The furniture is ours,
yes, and our clothes,

620
00:35:44,559 --> 00:35:46,527
but that's all.
That's all.

621
00:35:46,561 --> 00:35:49,496
- What about the paintings?
- No.

622
00:35:49,530 --> 00:35:51,122
Not my jewelry.

623
00:35:51,165 --> 00:35:53,531
The company bought those things
as investments.

624
00:35:53,568 --> 00:35:57,129
They were only ours to use.
I'm sorry. I'm sorry.

625
00:35:57,171 --> 00:36:00,663
Hey hey,
we got our health.

626
00:36:00,708 --> 00:36:04,041
We got each other.
We'll get by.

627
00:36:09,483 --> 00:36:12,748
Millie, Millie.

628
00:36:12,787 --> 00:36:14,755
I know you don't think
so right now, dear,

629
00:36:14,789 --> 00:36:17,223
but believe me,
this may be the best thing

630
00:36:17,258 --> 00:36:19,453
that ever happened
to us, and I mean it.

631
00:36:19,493 --> 00:36:21,484
For three separate
reasons.

632
00:36:21,529 --> 00:36:23,588
First, did you see
what happened down there?

633
00:36:23,631 --> 00:36:26,623
Did you see Michael
take over that situation?

634
00:36:26,667 --> 00:36:29,158
"We'll get by."
That's what he said.

635
00:36:29,203 --> 00:36:31,501
"We'll get by."
It's making a man of him.

636
00:36:31,539 --> 00:36:34,565
And second, you don't
know what this is doing for me.

637
00:36:34,609 --> 00:36:37,305
I feel invigorated
by the challenge,

638
00:36:37,345 --> 00:36:39,745
you know, rejuvenated.

639
00:36:39,780 --> 00:36:42,681
I feel like I'm being
given a second chance at life.

640
00:36:42,717 --> 00:36:45,242
- What's the third reason?
- I forget.

641
00:36:45,286 --> 00:36:48,517
Now don't you worry.
You know that I'm gonna look after you,

642
00:36:48,556 --> 00:36:52,151
- no matter what happens.
- Oh, Aram, what's gonna happen to us?

643
00:36:52,193 --> 00:36:54,923
Oh no, we'll be fine.
Darling, you'll be fine.

644
00:36:54,962 --> 00:36:57,328
You'll be...

645
00:36:57,365 --> 00:36:59,765
fine.

646
00:37:07,341 --> 00:37:09,571
Aram, where are we going?

647
00:37:09,610 --> 00:37:12,602
You'll see.
You'll see.

648
00:37:19,186 --> 00:37:21,211
Are we getting near?

649
00:37:21,255 --> 00:37:23,553
Yeah, very soon.

650
00:37:28,596 --> 00:37:30,655
All right,
we're almost there.

651
00:37:30,698 --> 00:37:32,757
- Millie, get ready to close your eyes.
- What?

652
00:37:32,800 --> 00:37:36,827
Just get ready to close your eyes.
It's gonna be a surprise.

653
00:37:36,871 --> 00:37:39,965
- Okay.
- Don't open them. Keep them closed.

654
00:37:40,007 --> 00:37:43,340
Michael, pay the cab,
would you? Okay.

655
00:37:45,680 --> 00:37:47,773
Okay, be careful.
Step on out. Now close 'em.

656
00:37:47,815 --> 00:37:49,783
All right,
up the curb. Okay.

657
00:37:49,817 --> 00:37:51,751
Wait a minute.
Okay.

658
00:37:51,786 --> 00:37:54,311
All right,
just keep 'em closed.

659
00:37:54,355 --> 00:37:57,051
Almost, okay.
Now you can open 'em.

660
00:37:57,091 --> 00:37:59,491
Huh, you see? Huh?
You recognize it?

661
00:37:59,527 --> 00:38:02,189
Michael, this is the building
your mother and I lived in

662
00:38:02,229 --> 00:38:05,062
when we first got married.
Millie, you're not gonna believe this.

663
00:38:05,099 --> 00:38:07,431
Our old apartment
was vacant.

664
00:38:07,468 --> 00:38:09,561
It's gonna be just
like coming home again.

665
00:38:09,603 --> 00:38:12,299
Come on, come on.

666
00:38:15,810 --> 00:38:17,801
We had some happy
times here,

667
00:38:17,845 --> 00:38:19,642
huh, Millie, huh?

668
00:38:19,680 --> 00:38:21,739
Yes.

669
00:38:23,751 --> 00:38:28,450
Somehow it seems
smaller than I remember.

670
00:38:30,791 --> 00:38:33,885
Five minus that...
833.

671
00:38:33,928 --> 00:38:37,659
Okay, now I didn't get as much as
I wanted for the rest of the furniture,

672
00:38:37,698 --> 00:38:40,326
but after paying the movers
one month's rent,

673
00:38:40,368 --> 00:38:44,168
we have a grand total of $833.
We're still ahead.

674
00:38:44,205 --> 00:38:47,606
Now, Millie, Michael,
come here a sec. Would you?

675
00:38:47,641 --> 00:38:49,609
I've made a detailed
budget here.

676
00:38:49,643 --> 00:38:52,544
I figure that we need $372 a week
for necessities.

677
00:38:52,580 --> 00:38:54,741
- You see?
- Yeah, I used to pay that for a belt.

678
00:38:54,782 --> 00:38:56,750
- Yes, I know.
- On sale.

679
00:38:56,784 --> 00:38:58,843
You will again soon,
I promise you.

680
00:38:58,886 --> 00:39:03,516
But in the meantime, our objective
is just to make $372 per week.

681
00:39:03,557 --> 00:39:06,993
Dad, I got...

682
00:39:07,028 --> 00:39:09,895
- I got a... I got a problem.
- Uh-huh.

683
00:39:09,930 --> 00:39:12,057
You see,
it's a little problem.

684
00:39:12,099 --> 00:39:15,398
Joey and I have this date to take these
two women out to dinner tonight,

685
00:39:15,436 --> 00:39:17,165
and I don't have
any money.

686
00:39:17,204 --> 00:39:19,434
Yeah, well, as I was saying,
Michael, right now

687
00:39:19,473 --> 00:39:23,273
all our money has
to go for necessities. We're poor.

688
00:39:23,310 --> 00:39:25,835
I know, but I made
the date when we were rich.

689
00:39:25,880 --> 00:39:28,974
You know what?
Never mind.

690
00:39:29,016 --> 00:39:31,382
Sorry, excuse me, Shag.
I'll ask Joey

691
00:39:31,419 --> 00:39:33,410
to lend me some money.

692
00:39:33,454 --> 00:39:37,220
No, hey, Michael,
we do not borrow.

693
00:39:37,258 --> 00:39:39,726
12 friends tried to help us.
I refused every one of 'em.

694
00:39:39,760 --> 00:39:41,728
- Aram...
- Excuse me, Millie, please.

695
00:39:41,762 --> 00:39:44,697
This family will get by through
its own efforts, son.

696
00:39:44,732 --> 00:39:46,757
- Hmm?
- You're right.

697
00:39:48,736 --> 00:39:50,761
Hey, Michael.

698
00:39:56,077 --> 00:39:57,908
Last time.

699
00:39:57,945 --> 00:40:00,038
As long as there's food
on that table, you can eat it.

700
00:40:00,081 --> 00:40:02,311
As long as we have
a roof, you can sleep under it.

701
00:40:02,349 --> 00:40:04,408
But anything you want
or need more than that,

702
00:40:04,452 --> 00:40:06,943
you supply the money,
okay, understood?

703
00:40:06,987 --> 00:40:08,955
Understood.

704
00:40:08,989 --> 00:40:10,957
There's Joey.
I'll see you later. Bye, Mom.

705
00:40:10,991 --> 00:40:12,982
Have a good time
and don't forget your key.

706
00:40:15,029 --> 00:40:18,362
Millie, that dinner was delicious.
It was just delicious.

707
00:40:18,399 --> 00:40:20,367
And I was afraid
you'd forgotten how to cook.

708
00:40:20,401 --> 00:40:21,993
I know.
Isn't it wonderful?

709
00:40:22,036 --> 00:40:24,732
After all these years, I haven't
forgotten how to cook or sweep floors

710
00:40:24,772 --> 00:40:27,263
or wash windows
or do laundry or scrub toilets.

711
00:40:27,308 --> 00:40:30,209
Isn't it wonderful?

712
00:40:34,315 --> 00:40:37,011
I'm sorry.
It must be very hard for you.

713
00:40:37,051 --> 00:40:40,020
And that's another thing I haven't
forgotten how to do...

714
00:40:40,054 --> 00:40:42,045
bitch.

715
00:40:55,369 --> 00:40:57,166
What?

716
00:40:57,204 --> 00:40:59,570
You making breakfast
in the kitchen,

717
00:40:59,607 --> 00:41:01,131
me going out
to look for a job

718
00:41:01,175 --> 00:41:04,440
and having no idea
how to pay next month's rent...

719
00:41:04,478 --> 00:41:07,379
life is an adventure again.
I feel 20 years old.

720
00:41:07,414 --> 00:41:09,712
I wish I could feel
20 years old.

721
00:41:09,750 --> 00:41:13,186
You'll always be
20 years old.

722
00:41:13,220 --> 00:41:15,484
- You do like me without the mustache?
- Very much.

723
00:41:15,523 --> 00:41:17,991
- I missed your nostrils.
- I think it's important.

724
00:41:18,025 --> 00:41:20,323
I want to look as young
as possible when I'm applying for jobs.

725
00:41:20,361 --> 00:41:23,558
- Michael up yet?
- No, I haven't seen him.

726
00:41:27,301 --> 00:41:29,895
Get up, Michael.
Michael.

727
00:41:31,205 --> 00:41:33,366
- Hey. Michael.
- What's the matter?

728
00:41:33,407 --> 00:41:35,375
Sorry. I'm on the way
to the employment agency.

729
00:41:35,409 --> 00:41:37,377
I thought maybe you'd
like to go with me.

730
00:41:37,411 --> 00:41:39,140
Huh?

731
00:41:39,180 --> 00:41:41,444
Oh, yeah
yeah, right.

732
00:41:41,482 --> 00:41:44,474
I really got to bed late.
Why don't you go alone?

733
00:41:44,518 --> 00:41:46,486
I'll go later
this afternoon.

734
00:41:46,520 --> 00:41:48,715
Well, the thing is
with an employment agency,

735
00:41:48,756 --> 00:41:50,724
it's better to get there
early in the morning.

736
00:41:50,758 --> 00:41:52,953
Get first crack
at those new jobs.

737
00:41:52,993 --> 00:41:56,121
- Afternoon's not so good.
- Yeah yeah, you're right.

738
00:41:56,163 --> 00:41:58,222
That makes sense.

739
00:41:58,265 --> 00:42:00,995
I'd better wait
till tomorrow.

740
00:42:01,035 --> 00:42:03,367
Hey, good luck.

741
00:42:07,474 --> 00:42:09,442
- Michael.
- Yeah.

742
00:42:09,476 --> 00:42:13,003
The other day when I said that
we weren't rich anymore,

743
00:42:13,047 --> 00:42:16,983
you put your arm
around me and you said, "We'll get by."

744
00:42:18,352 --> 00:42:20,320
What exactly
did you mean by that?

745
00:42:20,354 --> 00:42:24,290
I meant you'll find a way
to make us rich again.

746
00:42:36,537 --> 00:42:39,370
Okay,
Mr. Katourian, age?

747
00:42:39,406 --> 00:42:40,964
59... 5.

748
00:42:41,008 --> 00:42:44,102
55.

749
00:42:44,144 --> 00:42:46,112
Previous job experience?

750
00:42:46,146 --> 00:42:48,706
When I was younger,
I did everything.

751
00:42:48,749 --> 00:42:50,842
I sold insurance,
drove trucks,

752
00:42:50,884 --> 00:42:52,852
did dishes,
you name it.

753
00:42:52,886 --> 00:42:55,514
What was your most
recent employment?

754
00:42:56,890 --> 00:43:00,826
Actually, chairman
of the board of a company.

755
00:43:00,861 --> 00:43:03,853
We don't get a lot
of calls for that.

756
00:43:03,897 --> 00:43:05,524
No, of course not.

757
00:43:05,566 --> 00:43:09,058
Chairman of the board.

758
00:43:09,103 --> 00:43:12,231
I'll take anything you got.
I'm just looking for work.

759
00:43:12,273 --> 00:43:13,968
Approximate earnings
last year.

760
00:43:14,008 --> 00:43:15,942
Oh, tough one.

761
00:43:15,976 --> 00:43:18,035
What with stock
dividends and bonuses...

762
00:43:18,078 --> 00:43:19,670
Ballpark figure.

763
00:43:19,713 --> 00:43:22,147
Ballpark... three mil.

764
00:43:22,182 --> 00:43:24,480
Well, 3.2.

765
00:43:24,518 --> 00:43:27,578
Obviously, I'm not expecting
to earn anywhere near that much.

766
00:43:27,621 --> 00:43:30,283
That does
make it easier.

767
00:43:40,100 --> 00:43:43,661
Hey, man, do me a favor.
Don't have such a nice day.

768
00:43:49,310 --> 00:43:52,040
Minimum wage, of course,
but it paid for supper.

769
00:43:52,079 --> 00:43:55,981
Oh, the other interview I had,
that is very promising.

770
00:43:56,016 --> 00:43:58,985
This fella is starting
an express delivery service downtown,

771
00:43:59,019 --> 00:44:01,044
like in Manhattan,
you know, on bicycles,

772
00:44:01,088 --> 00:44:03,318
so you can get through
the traffic fast.

773
00:44:03,357 --> 00:44:06,258
Salary plus a dollar
a delivery and tips.

774
00:44:06,293 --> 00:44:09,421
Anyhow, with that, plus three,
four nights a week at the car wash,

775
00:44:09,463 --> 00:44:12,227
and then on Saturdays,
a shoe store.

776
00:44:12,266 --> 00:44:14,325
They need extra help.
With those three jobs,

777
00:44:14,368 --> 00:44:17,633
plus what you're gonna bring in,
I think we can meet expenses each week,

778
00:44:17,671 --> 00:44:20,105
- put a little away for the business.
- What business?

779
00:44:20,140 --> 00:44:22,131
I don't know,
but it'll be good.

780
00:44:22,176 --> 00:44:25,304
Just like I came up with the health
food supermarkets 20 years ago.

781
00:44:25,346 --> 00:44:28,611
I'll come up with right idea,
and I will make it a reality.

782
00:44:28,649 --> 00:44:31,243
Why not the food business?
You already know it.

783
00:44:31,285 --> 00:44:34,812
Exactly, I know it and I've done it.
That's no challenge, dear.

784
00:44:34,855 --> 00:44:37,756
Michael, give me
a cookie, please.

785
00:44:37,791 --> 00:44:40,487
Thanks.

786
00:44:42,463 --> 00:44:45,364
Hey, Dad, going through
what you did,

787
00:44:45,399 --> 00:44:47,367
I mean losing
everything like that,

788
00:44:47,401 --> 00:44:50,029
yet refusing to be
beat, hanging tough...

789
00:44:50,070 --> 00:44:52,630
well, I just think

790
00:44:52,673 --> 00:44:54,573
you're terrific.

791
00:44:54,608 --> 00:44:56,576
You're terrific
too, Michael.

792
00:44:56,610 --> 00:44:59,602
You just haven't had a chance
to find out how terrific you are.

793
00:44:59,646 --> 00:45:02,012
I don't know. Your drive,
your determination,

794
00:45:02,049 --> 00:45:04,449
- I don't seem to have any of that.
- Oh, you have it.

795
00:45:04,485 --> 00:45:07,113
It's in our blood.
Trust me.

796
00:45:07,154 --> 00:45:10,146
Okay, well, I guess
I'd better get to bed early

797
00:45:10,190 --> 00:45:13,250
if I'm gonna be the first
one at that employment office tomorrow.

798
00:45:13,293 --> 00:45:15,056
- Good night, Dad.
- Good night.

799
00:45:15,095 --> 00:45:17,723
- Good night, Mom.
- Good night.

800
00:45:20,234 --> 00:45:23,601
And you were
worried about him.

801
00:45:29,810 --> 00:45:33,871
I was so proud
of Michael that night.

802
00:45:33,914 --> 00:45:36,246
Excuse me a second.
I think I see lunch.

803
00:45:40,087 --> 00:45:42,317
- Do you need any help?
- No, I'm fine.

804
00:45:42,356 --> 00:45:45,450
Maybe you could help me.
I haven't eaten in two days.

805
00:45:45,492 --> 00:45:47,790
- Could you spare a little change?
- Sorry, no.

806
00:45:49,430 --> 00:45:53,491
Oh, no wonder. Don't ever stand near
me when I'm begging.

807
00:45:53,534 --> 00:45:54,899
Why?

808
00:45:54,935 --> 00:45:57,165
A guy sees one bum,
he feels compassion.

809
00:45:57,204 --> 00:46:00,037
He sees two, he figures
it's a social problem,

810
00:46:00,073 --> 00:46:02,439
- let the government take care of it.
- Oh, sorry.

811
00:46:02,476 --> 00:46:05,411
So go on. Michael was going to
the employment office.

812
00:46:05,446 --> 00:46:09,439
Oh, yeah, I couldn't wait
to see what happened.

813
00:46:11,285 --> 00:46:13,253
He's coming, Millie.
He's coming.

814
00:46:15,956 --> 00:46:19,824
- Hi Dad. Hi Mom.
- Hi. Hey there.

815
00:46:19,860 --> 00:46:21,885
How did it go today
at the employment agency?

816
00:46:21,929 --> 00:46:24,022
It was fine. I'm in kind of
a hurry, though.

817
00:46:24,064 --> 00:46:26,760
- I got a date.
- Wait a minute.

818
00:46:26,800 --> 00:46:29,325
Did you hear that, Millie.
Michael has money for a date.

819
00:46:29,369 --> 00:46:31,337
- Did you get a job?
- Mmm-hmm.

820
00:46:31,371 --> 00:46:34,363
Oh God, that's wonderful.
You spend the money you earn,

821
00:46:34,408 --> 00:46:36,376
'cause you deserve it.
What kind of job?

822
00:46:36,410 --> 00:46:38,275
Well, it was kind
of an office...

823
00:46:38,312 --> 00:46:41,611
That's past tense, "was."
You did get a job?

824
00:46:41,648 --> 00:46:44,845
- Yeah.
- You showed up? You started to work?

825
00:46:44,885 --> 00:46:47,046
Yeah, I started work,
and then I quit.

826
00:46:47,087 --> 00:46:49,783
- You quit?
- Well, Dad, the boss was a real jerk.

827
00:46:49,823 --> 00:46:52,451
Well, of course he was a jerk.
All bosses are jerks.

828
00:46:52,493 --> 00:46:55,690
Hopefully, someday you'll become
a jerk. What did he do?

829
00:46:55,729 --> 00:46:58,892
Well, he kept ordering me around.
Do this, do that.

830
00:46:58,932 --> 00:47:01,093
It was demeaning.
It was insulting.

831
00:47:01,134 --> 00:47:04,934
Oh, how long did you
suffer these demeaning insults?

832
00:47:04,972 --> 00:47:06,940
I don't know.
20 minutes, half-hour.

833
00:47:06,974 --> 00:47:09,943
But it's okay. I figured out another
way to make some money.

834
00:47:09,977 --> 00:47:11,274
Another job?

835
00:47:11,311 --> 00:47:13,211
No, I don't want to go
through that again.

836
00:47:13,247 --> 00:47:16,648
I found this secondhand clothing store.
I took in a bunch of my clothes.

837
00:47:16,683 --> 00:47:18,810
I got over $100.

838
00:47:21,488 --> 00:47:23,752
Oh! No!

839
00:47:42,509 --> 00:47:45,910
Hello.
Hey, Joey, how you doing?

840
00:47:45,946 --> 00:47:48,414
Nah, I don't feel like
going to a movie tonight.

841
00:47:48,448 --> 00:47:50,643
I'm just gonna stay
around the house.

842
00:47:50,684 --> 00:47:53,050
I do love Woody Allen.

843
00:47:53,086 --> 00:47:55,646
I just don't love
him tonight.

844
00:47:55,689 --> 00:47:57,782
Okay,
I'll see you later.

845
00:48:04,932 --> 00:48:08,231
You'd like to see that
movie, wouldn't you?

846
00:48:08,268 --> 00:48:09,792
Yeah.

847
00:48:09,836 --> 00:48:13,533
Movies cost money,
don't they?

848
00:48:13,574 --> 00:48:15,974
Yeah.

849
00:48:16,009 --> 00:48:20,173
You're all out
of money, aren't you?

850
00:48:21,548 --> 00:48:23,539
Oh yeah.

851
00:48:26,253 --> 00:48:29,051
I guess if you
want those things that you like,

852
00:48:29,089 --> 00:48:33,549
you'll have to get a job
and earn some money, won't you?

853
00:48:35,629 --> 00:48:37,620
There's gotta be
a better way.

854
00:48:37,664 --> 00:48:41,464
No, Michael, no, there is
no better way, period.

855
00:48:41,501 --> 00:48:43,298
That's the way
the world is.

856
00:48:43,337 --> 00:48:46,602
The way the world has always been.
Man must work.

857
00:48:46,640 --> 00:48:48,767
Can't be right, Dad.

858
00:48:48,809 --> 00:48:50,777
The human race
has gotten along

859
00:48:50,811 --> 00:48:54,042
for hundreds of thousands
of years without work.

860
00:48:54,081 --> 00:48:56,606
If a guy needed food,
he went out and he hunted.

861
00:48:56,650 --> 00:48:59,312
If he needed shelter,
okay, he built one.

862
00:48:59,353 --> 00:49:03,585
That was it. The rest of his time,
he did what he felt like.

863
00:49:03,624 --> 00:49:07,185
Chased girls or he drew pictures
of animals in caves.

864
00:49:07,227 --> 00:49:09,320
He had no concept
of work.

865
00:49:09,363 --> 00:49:12,298
Do you know that
even today in some African tribes,

866
00:49:12,332 --> 00:49:14,493
and even in
the Eskimo language,

867
00:49:14,534 --> 00:49:17,503
- no such word as work?
- What do you know from Eskimos?

868
00:49:17,537 --> 00:49:20,165
Well, in college,
I took this course in anthropology.

869
00:49:20,207 --> 00:49:22,607
- So?
- So you know how work got started?

870
00:49:22,643 --> 00:49:27,171
One day this really big guy
went up to this little guy and said,

871
00:49:27,214 --> 00:49:29,614
"Hey, buddy, I got
a proposition for ya.

872
00:49:29,650 --> 00:49:33,450
From now on, you do all my hunting
for me. You do all my fishing for me.

873
00:49:33,487 --> 00:49:37,184
You clean up my cave for me and you do
whatever else I tell you to do, okay?"

874
00:49:37,224 --> 00:49:39,749
The little guy said,
"Well, gee, I don't know.

875
00:49:39,793 --> 00:49:41,761
What do I get out
of it?"

876
00:49:41,795 --> 00:49:44,855
And the big guy said,
"If you do all these things for me,

877
00:49:44,898 --> 00:49:46,889
I won't bash your head
in with this rock."

878
00:49:46,933 --> 00:49:49,629
And the little guy said,
"That sounds pretty good to me."

879
00:49:49,670 --> 00:49:51,467
And boom, that's
how work got started.

880
00:49:51,505 --> 00:49:54,269
And then one day,
the little guy's girlfriend went to him

881
00:49:54,307 --> 00:49:56,775
and said, "Honey,
why are you doing all this stuff?"

882
00:49:56,810 --> 00:49:58,778
He didn't want
to seem like a wimp.

883
00:49:58,812 --> 00:50:01,576
So he said,
"Because it's good.

884
00:50:01,615 --> 00:50:04,049
Work is a noble thing
for man to do."

885
00:50:04,084 --> 00:50:05,984
And that's how
the work ethic got started.

886
00:50:06,019 --> 00:50:07,452
Yes, work is a noble thing.

887
00:50:07,487 --> 00:50:09,284
It is the most noble
thing in the world.

888
00:50:09,322 --> 00:50:11,950
- Dad, that's your opinion.
- Who would disagree?

889
00:50:11,992 --> 00:50:13,755
- Socrates, for one.
- Socrates?

890
00:50:13,794 --> 00:50:16,194
Socrates. In his day,
work was for slaves.

891
00:50:16,229 --> 00:50:19,323
For inferior beings who
did all the menial tasks

892
00:50:19,366 --> 00:50:23,029
so that the superior
Greeks would be free to pursue art

893
00:50:23,070 --> 00:50:26,233
and philosophy
and statecraft.

894
00:50:26,273 --> 00:50:30,004
All through Europe, up to the 20th
century, if work was so noble,

895
00:50:30,043 --> 00:50:33,240
how come you never
saw any of the nobility doing it, hmm?

896
00:50:33,280 --> 00:50:35,805
What is with these Eskimos
and superior Greeks?

897
00:50:35,849 --> 00:50:37,817
This is the United States.

898
00:50:37,851 --> 00:50:40,513
And this is today.
People think differently, Michael.

899
00:50:40,554 --> 00:50:42,385
Not everybody.

900
00:50:42,422 --> 00:50:44,822
You can't change the world
you live in, Michael.

901
00:50:44,858 --> 00:50:48,624
And everybody knows
that work is good for man.

902
00:50:48,662 --> 00:50:51,358
Like everybody in your
grandfather's village

903
00:50:51,398 --> 00:50:54,333
knew that they were safe
from the Turks?

904
00:50:55,936 --> 00:50:58,632
Are you sure you don't
want to be a lawyer?

905
00:50:58,672 --> 00:51:01,766
Here you go.
Good luck.

906
00:51:29,736 --> 00:51:32,637
Whoa!
Whoa!

907
00:51:32,672 --> 00:51:35,698
Hey, wanna go around it
and not through it?

908
00:51:35,742 --> 00:51:37,903
I'm sorry.

909
00:52:31,431 --> 00:52:33,524
Hey, man, come on.
Get out of the way!

910
00:52:33,567 --> 00:52:35,558
Trying to get through.

911
00:52:58,592 --> 00:53:01,220
Oh my God.
Are you okay?

912
00:53:01,261 --> 00:53:03,161
Oh yeah. Oh yeah.

913
00:53:03,196 --> 00:53:04,891
- Oh yeah. Oh yeah.
- Are you sure?

914
00:53:04,931 --> 00:53:07,399
Long as I don't have
to sit down for the next 20 years,

915
00:53:07,434 --> 00:53:09,402
I'll be okay.
I'm fine.

916
00:53:09,436 --> 00:53:12,701
I'll be all right. It's like somebody
used a pineapple as a probe.

917
00:53:12,739 --> 00:53:15,435
Pillow pillow, put the pillow down.
Put the pillow down.

918
00:53:15,475 --> 00:53:17,534
Put the pillow down.
That's it. That's it.

919
00:53:20,780 --> 00:53:23,613
You are not going
back to that job.

920
00:53:23,650 --> 00:53:26,050
No, it's just I did
too many miles the first day.

921
00:53:26,086 --> 00:53:28,816
My body will adjust.

922
00:53:28,855 --> 00:53:30,846
Make me a drink.

923
00:53:44,905 --> 00:53:48,898
Until the pain set in,
I really enjoyed the day.

924
00:53:48,942 --> 00:53:51,638
It was nice riding out
there in the open air,

925
00:53:51,678 --> 00:53:54,977
and the people going by,

926
00:53:55,015 --> 00:53:56,983
all the activity.

927
00:53:57,017 --> 00:53:59,986
The trees passing by.

928
00:54:00,020 --> 00:54:02,352
Heck of a lot nicer
than that damned exercycle.

929
00:54:02,389 --> 00:54:05,449
You know, sitting there
looking at nothing but reruns on the...

930
00:54:07,260 --> 00:54:09,285
television.

931
00:54:11,898 --> 00:54:14,765
- Oh oh oh! That's it!
- What is it?

932
00:54:14,801 --> 00:54:17,326
That is it. Michael, come on
out here, would you?

933
00:54:17,370 --> 00:54:20,305
Hurry up, quick. This is the new
business that I'm going into.

934
00:54:20,340 --> 00:54:24,037
Here, listen to this idea.
Video bicycle tours.

935
00:54:24,077 --> 00:54:26,307
We make videos of what
a biker would see

936
00:54:26,346 --> 00:54:28,109
while he was riding
through London

937
00:54:28,148 --> 00:54:29,638
or Rome,
the French countryside,

938
00:54:29,683 --> 00:54:32,015
whatever, you name it.
We sell those videos

939
00:54:32,052 --> 00:54:33,883
to the people that own
the exercycles.

940
00:54:33,920 --> 00:54:35,888
They go home.
They put it into their set

941
00:54:35,922 --> 00:54:40,416
and instead of boring exercise,
every workout becomes a holiday.

942
00:54:40,460 --> 00:54:44,863
- Do enough people own these exercycles?
- There must be millions.

943
00:54:44,898 --> 00:54:46,957
Wait a minute.

944
00:54:47,000 --> 00:54:49,127
We could develop
a luxury exercycle.

945
00:54:49,169 --> 00:54:51,694
You know, with the TV set
built right on it.

946
00:54:51,738 --> 00:54:54,366
Two, three of 'em.
Yeah, different points of view.

947
00:54:54,407 --> 00:54:57,137
Left, right and center.
Sensational.

948
00:54:57,177 --> 00:55:00,510
You could go around the world
without ever leaving your bedroom.

949
00:55:00,547 --> 00:55:02,845
Sunday we'll take the camera,
we'll go to the park

950
00:55:02,882 --> 00:55:05,817
- and we'll try it out on my bike, huh?
- Okay, sounds great.

951
00:55:05,852 --> 00:55:08,980
One problem, I don't think
you'd use your video camera on the bike.

952
00:55:09,022 --> 00:55:11,388
The picture would get wobbly.
I know how to fix it.

953
00:55:11,424 --> 00:55:14,222
- Why don't you let me handle it?
- Well, thank you, Michael.

954
00:55:14,260 --> 00:55:16,728
As a matter of fact,
a buddy of mine is in film school.

955
